Data Science Pipeline Tutorial:
What Are the World's Rising National Film Industries?

One of the classes I took this semester was FILM298D: Film Art in a Global Society. The course was, as you might guess, about cinema around the globe, giving a broad view of modern film industries across many countries. I got to see a lot of good movies, but I was saddened to see that most of them were not well known outside of film festivals and critical circles, as most countries' everyday movie theaters and streaming options are dominated by American and other Anglophone films. However, I also heard that the national film industries of many non-Anglophone countries are growing, and this inspired me to look at the data of global film production to determine just which countries' film industries are rising and how. In this tutorial I will seek to determine which countries' film industries are growing the fastest, in terms of total pictures produced annually, pictures produced intranationally, and pictures produced via international coproductions.

Tim Hicks

Data Scraping

We will be getting national film data from the UNESCO Institute for Statistics, available at http://data.uis.unesco.org/. The table I want to use is "Culture/Feature Films/Feature Films (full dataset)". I have downloaded the table and have reuploaded it to GitHub for use here. This data set covers the film production of most countries in the world from 2011 to 2017.

Managing the Data

At over 30,000 rows of information, we suddenly have a lot of data! This single UNESCO table contains 76 different categories—indicated by the "Indicator" column—of information on feature film production, distribution of feature films, cinema infrastructure, and exhibition of feature films, and while all of it is interesting, most of it is extraneous for our purposes here. So, to make this data set more managable, I will extract three smaller tables containing the information we want. We can discard the rest.

What is the information we want? In this analysis we are looking at three main figures:

  • Total number of feature films produced by each country each year
  • Number of feature films that are produced 100% intranationally by each country each year
  • Number of feature films that are produced as international coproductions by each country each year
To be "produced by" a given country, at least one of a film's producers must be of that country. The film does not have to be shot, edited, or anything else in that country, merely funded there. This means that films that are international coproductions have multiple producers of multiple national origins.

First, the total number of feature films produced by each country each year. This value will be equal to the sum of the intranational productions and the coproductions of each country each year, so we shouldn't have to extract this table at all if we didn't want to, since we can just derive the value ourselves from our other data. But there are some countries and years for which this is the only data we have, with no additional breakdowns into domestic vs. international productions, so we need to take this table by itself as well if we want to have maximum access to the data.

Tidying the Data

Now that we have just the data we want, we can begin working with it, right? If you want to, sure. But the data is still a bit obtuse, so I want to refine it a bit further. At the moment, each of our three tables has multiple rows for each year and multiple rows for each country, which makes it a bit difficult to process or even look at the data without some unnecessary stress. So to resolve that, I am pivoting each of the tables so that there is one row for each year and one column for each country. Then I am dropping the "Value" super-header, since it adds no new information. This way it will be easy to look up the number of films of any type produced by any country in any year without having to use any more code than we have to.

In [8]:
natfilms = natfilms.pivot(index='Time', columns='Country')
natfilms.columns = natfilms.columns.droplevel()
In [9]:
intrafilms = intrafilms.pivot(index='Time', columns='Country')
intrafilms.columns = intrafilms.columns.droplevel()
In [10]:
cofilms = cofilms.pivot(index='Time', columns='Country')
cofilms.columns = cofilms.columns.droplevel()

There's one more thing I want to address before we move on, and that's countries for which there is no data saying they produced any films of a given type at all between 2011 and 2017. Since Andorra's film industry seems to have been completely dead for the whole period we are looking at, it is no use including it in our data, so I want to purge it and all others like it from our tables.

Preliminary Data Representation

Okay, now that we are done kneading the data, we can get to the interesting parts. The first of those is creating a basic visual representation of the data so we can get a better sense of what we are working with.

    x = natfilms[c]
    # Plot the data trend for a given country as a line

Data Analysis

I didn't label the country names corresponding to the points on the graphs above because there aren't enough distinct colors in the visible spectrum to make them all differentiable on a chart. But these are just preliminary visualizations and will not be our most important graphs, so it's not the worst thing. Referring back to the data in the tables, I'll translate the first graph for you, the one about total films produced each year.

That's India in that line of dots soaring far above everyone else, rising from about 1250 to 2000. Below India is a series of runners-up for the title of most feature films per year: China, the United States, and Japan, plus one really good year each for Nigeria and South Korea. Below these is a gap before everyone else is clustered at the bottom, spread from 0 to about 350.
India's numbers are rapidly rising, China's and Japan's are slowly rising, and the US's are slowly falling. It is nearly impossible to make an estimate about the growth rates of the rest of the countries at this point. To do that, we need to calculate a line of best fit for each nation's film production numbers and determine which has the highest slope. We will do that in the next step, but first, let's also examine the other two graphs.

Looking at the intranationally-produced films graph, India is again the major outlier. There is only data for India in this category in two years, 2014 and 2015, but we can see that in those years pretty much all of India's massive number of films were produced 100% in India. Over a thousand intranational films behind India is the United States, for which the vast majority of its films are intranationally-produced, although the coproduction graph shows that the US still coproduces more of its films than any other country, with the occasional exception of France. All other countries fow which we have data produce no more than about 250 intranational films per year and up to a hundred coproductions per year, though most make far fewer.

Once we calculate which countries' film industries are growing the fastest, we can use this data to determine whether this rising success is due primarily to a focus on intranational productions, international coproductions, or a relatively even mix of both. So far it seems like India's insane film industry is probably growing the fastest in addition to being the biggest, but it is unclear what countries will be the runners-up. To determine that—as well as whether India truly is the current king of cinematic growth—we will need to use hypothesis testing and machine learning.

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning

In [16]:
filmgrowth = pd.DataFrame(np.array([[np.NaN] * len(natfilms.columns.values)]),
                          columns=natfilms.columns.values)
filmgrowth = filmgrowth.rename(index={0: 'Growth Coefficient'})

for c in natfilms.columns.values:
    ind = []
    dep = []
    for y in natfilms.index.values:
        val = natfilms.at[y,c]
        if not(pd.isnull(val)):
            ind.append([y])
            dep.append(val)
    lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    lm.fit(ind, dep)
    filmgrowth.at['Growth Coefficient', c] = lm.coef_[0]

wmap = folium.Map()
for c in list(filmgrowth.columns.values):
    lat = coords.at[c,'Latitude']
    lon = coords.at[c,'Longitude']
    if isinstance(lat, pd.core.series.Series):
        lat = lat[0]
        lon = lon[0]
    col = 'purple'
    rate = filmgrowth.at['Growth Coefficient',c]
    if rate <= -10:
         col = 'red'
    elif rate <= 0:
        col = 'orange'
    elif rate <= 10:
        col = 'lightblue'
    elif rate <= 20:
        col = 'lightgreen'
    elif rate <= 30:
        col = 'green'
    elif rate <= 50:
        col = 'darkgreen'
    info = '7-Year Growth Coefficient:\n' + str(filmgrowth.at['Growth Coefficient',c])
    folium.Marker([lat, lon],popup=info,tooltip=c,icon=folium.Icon(color=col,icon='film')).add_to(wmap)

Further Data Analysis

Conclusion

Just because the number of films per year in the US is going down does not mean that the American film industry is shrinking; rathher, larger amounts of money are increasingly going to fewer and fewer films each year. American films are becoming more of a gamble. But what we are interested in today is which countries are expanding the number of films they make? While American movie producers are taking larger risks on a relatively small number of films by well-known filmmakers working with well-known properties (generally aiming for "safe bet" films), which countries are becoming more adventurous and growing their film industries in diversity? And how are they mixing intranational productions with coproductions?
